=============================================
Simple Assorion [User] Interface Layer (SAIL)
=============================================

This folder is dedicated to housing the code for the -
home-grown interface used for the charting state.

For now this is part of the Assorion Engine codebase, -
but it can (and probably will be) isolated into it's -
own repository for use in other projects.

=============================================

Why?

Mostly for two reasons:
1) It removes a dependency (Assorion now only requires -
   Flixel, Lime, and OpenFL).
2) And the more real answer: Because Flixel UI has -
   to be one of the most painful ways of writing UI code.

=============================================

How does SAIL work?

It's extremely simple. Fundamentally, it all hinges -
on "SIGeneric", which contains properties that apply -
to every part of the UI.

"SIContainer" is a type which is designed to hold -
other components. A container has all of it's children -
hinge on one of four directions (top left, top right, -
bottom left, bottom right). A container also gets to -
define it's spacing. For example: 5 pixels between each -
component.

Most components (like buttons, checkboxes, type-in boxes) -
are generic components that inherit directly off of SIGeneric.
But some other components (like dropdowns, or steppers) are -
essentially a combination of multiple other components, -
thus they are secretly just a SIContainer that holds them -
in disguise.

Positioning is not handled through coordinates, instead -
each SIGeneric (or related classes) have two properties:
- Reference: Another component to base this position off,
- Anchor: An enum which controls the direction from the -
  reference that this component which go.

If no reference is supplied, the component will take on the -
position of the corner specified by it's parent container.

Lastly; A master container is used to hold all of the -
UI. But must rely on a parent state in order to add it, and -
update it.

=============================================

Could/Should SAIL be used in other projects?

Maybe, maybe not. It does still rely on Flixel to provide -
sprites and groups to components but that could be isolated -
for use in other engines like heaps (potentially).

In terms of "should": Maybe, maybe not. It depends on your -
needs. If you need a very quick simple UI to hack together, -
then this could be a good starting point.
If you need a mature UI library, perhaps use something else, -
like HaxeUI. However like always, the overall goal for Assorion -
is simplicity, no need for any complicated UI libraries.

